CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, September 1, 1956, pg. 1, reads: "What About This? - Objecting citizens, who no longer sport a family 'coat-of-arms,' consisting of a cotton patch with bandana rampant, complained that the stereotyped name of this street in East Liberty, 'Rastus Way'... is an insult and should be changed.  The two lone houses (right photo) have front entrances on the dirt alley, which was named in 1910, while other residences face nicely-kept Julius St. 'Rastus Way' has no place in a city which brags about its 'New Look' and general renaissance program.  The name should be changed. Don't you think? - Harris Photos."
TitMainTitle: Dirt street, Rastus Way, with houses in background, and industrial area on right, East Liberty
